<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="181" pageId="17" pageNumber="180" type="discussion">
<paragraph lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="181" pageId="17" pageNumber="180">
Comments: This ♀ cannot be reliably identified or described as a new species. On the basis of its copulatory organs (
<figureCitation box="[521,603,1089,1116]" captionStart="Figs 70 – 72" captionStartId="17.[181,221,1628,1650]" captionTargetBox="[196,1133,1193,1603]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[187,1147,1186,1607]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figs 70 – 72. Meleon sp. from Uganda, female: (70) epigyne, ventral view; (71) spermathecae, dorsal view; (72) ditto, dorsolateral view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." pageId="17" pageNumber="180">
Fig. 
<number box="[573,603,1089,1116]" pageId="17" pageNumber="180" value="70.0">70</number>
</figureCitation>
), it is most close to, but clearly distinct from, 
<taxonomicName authority="Wijesinghe 1994" authorityName="Wijesinghe" authorityYear="1994" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Meleon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solitaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="180">M. solitaria</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[293,355,1123,1148]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="180">sensu</emphasis>
Wijesinghe 
<number box="[497,557,1121,1148]" pageId="17" pageNumber="180" value="1994.0">1994</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
. It can be easily distinguished from the ♀ 
<typeStatus box="[1043,1141,1121,1148]" pageId="17" pageNumber="180">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis box="[174,297,205,232]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName box="[174,297,205,232]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Meleon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solitaria">P. solitaria</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
by the ovoid shape of the spermathecae (cf. 
<figureCitation box="[801,927,205,232]" captionStart="Figs 70 – 72" captionStartId="17.[181,221,1628,1650]" captionTargetBox="[196,1133,1193,1603]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[187,1147,1186,1607]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figs 70 – 72. Meleon sp. from Uganda, female: (70) epigyne, ventral view; (71) spermathecae, dorsal view; (72) ditto, dorsolateral view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." pageId="18" pageNumber="181">Figs 71, 72</figureCitation>
and figs 
<quantity box="[1030,1104,205,232]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" metricValueMax="1.524" metricValueMin="1.016" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" unit="in" value="5.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.0">4–6 in</quantity>
Wijesinghe 
<number box="[277,337,237,264]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" value="1994.0">1994</number>
). However, the current conception of the latter species is based on the assumption that the ♀ 
<typeStatus box="[402,500,269,296]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis box="[540,715,269,296]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName box="[540,715,269,296]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Portia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solitaria">Portia solitaria</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
from Zaire and the ♂ 
<typeStatus box="[974,1072,269,296]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Wanless, 1978" authorityName="Wanless" authorityYear="1978" box="[144,477,301,328]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Portia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falsifera">
<emphasis box="[144,312,301,328]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">Portia falsifera</emphasis>
Wanless, 
<number box="[421,477,302,328]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" value="1978.0">1978</number>
</taxonomicName>
from Uganda belong to the same species (see Wijesinghe 
<number box="[144,204,334,360]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" value="1994.0">1994</number>
: 
<number box="[213,245,333,360]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" value="60.0">60</number>
). On the contrary, it is very likely that our ♀ from Uganda and the ♂ 
<typeStatus box="[1006,1104,333,360]" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis box="[173,293,365,392]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName box="[173,293,365,392]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Portia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falsifera">P. falsifera</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
belong to the same taxon. If so, the latter name should be revalidated and removed from the synonymy with 
<emphasis box="[536,670,397,424]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName box="[536,670,397,424]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Portia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solitaria">M. solitaria</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. Thus, the studied ♀ belongs either to 
<emphasis box="[144,275,429,456]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName box="[144,275,429,456]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Portia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falsifera">M. falsifera</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
or to a new species. The matter can be finally decided when a sample of 
<emphasis box="[144,274,461,488]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName box="[144,274,461,488]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Portia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falsifera">M. falsifera</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
with both sexes has been collected.
</paragraph>
